<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike many still wines, <strong>prosecco's aging potential varies dramatically</strong> depending on quality level and production method. Understanding these differences is crucial for maximizing your investment in different prosecco styles.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Quality Level</h3>
<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> should be consumed within 2-3 years of vintage, as the fresh fruit character and effervescence are its primary assets. <strong>Prosecco DOCG from Conegliano Valdobbiadene</strong> can age 3-5 years, particularly single-vineyard bottlings like those from Cartizze. <strong>Franciacorta DOCG</strong>, produced using méthode champenoise, offers the greatest aging potential at 7-12 years for vintage releases and up to 15 years for premium cuvées.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p>Most prosecco DOC peaks within the first year after purchase, when primary fruit flavors of green apple and pear remain vibrant. Conegliano Valdobbiadene prosecco develops optimal complexity between years 2-4, while Franciacorta typically reaches its stride after 5-7 years of aging, when autolytic characters from extended lees contact fully integrate.</p>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>
<p>As prosecco ages, <strong>bright citrus notes evolve into honeyed, nutty complexity</strong>. The mousse becomes more refined and persistent, particularly in traditional method wines. However, tank-method prosecco (Charmat) loses its signature freshness relatively quickly, with fruit flavors flattening after 3-4 years.</p>

<h3>Proper Storage</h3>
<p>Store prosecco at <strong>50-55°F with 70% humidity</strong>, laying bottles horizontally to keep corks moist. Avoid light exposure and temperature fluctuations, which can cause premature oxidation and loss of pressure.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>
<p>Properly aged prosecco develops golden hues and toasty complexity while maintaining bright acidity. <strong>Warning signs include</strong> brown coloration, musty aromas, or significantly diminished bubbles, indicating oxidation or cork failure.</p>

