    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is buying old Prosecco or storing it too long – these wines are meant to be consumed within 1-2 years of purchase for optimal freshness. Many people also confuse price with quality without understanding the DOCG/DOC classifications. Always check the vintage date and choose the most recent year available, as Prosecco's appeal lies in its bright, youthful fruit character rather than aging complexity.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I identify high-quality Prosecco from the label alone?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for "DOCG" designation (Conegliano-Valdobbiadene or Asolo), recent vintage dates (within 2 years), and specific producer names rather than generic brand labels. Terms like "Rive" indicate single-vineyard sites and higher quality, while "Cartizze" represents the most prestigious subzone. Avoid bottles without clear origin information or those using terms like "Prosecco-style" which indicate non-authentic products.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I substitute Prosecco for Champagne in cocktails and recipes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Prosecco works excellently in most sparkling cocktails like Bellinis, Aperol Spritzes, and mimosas due to its lighter, fruitier profile and lower alcohol content. However, for recipes requiring more structure and complexity (like classic Champagne cocktails), the substitution may lack depth. Prosecco's sweeter fruit character also pairs differently with food, making it better for lighter fare than rich, complex dishes that benefit from Champagne's acidity and minerality.</p>
